---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Evidence-Based Treatments">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>Evidence-Based Treatments</h1>

    <p>
      If neuroplastic pain is a problem of learned neural pathways, then the solution involves 
      <strong>unlearning</strong> those pathways. The most effective treatments directly target 
      the brain and nervous system rather than the body.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">1. Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)</h3>
      <p>PRT teaches you to reinterpret pain signals as false alarms rather than signs of danger. It combines mindfulness, cognitive reappraisal, and gradual re-exposure to movement. The landmark trial (Ashar et al., 2022) found <strong>66% of participants pain-free after 4 weeks</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">2. Pain Neuroscience Education (PNE)</h3>
      <p>Simply learning how pain works reduces pain, fear, and disability. Studies show that understanding central sensitization is itself therapeutic — it reduces catastrophizing and fear of movement. This is why reading this site is a step in the right direction.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">3. Emotional Awareness and Expression Therapy (EAET)</h3>
      <p>EAET focuses on identifying and expressing emotions that may be contributing to pain — often trauma, anger, grief, or stress that got stuck. It helps the nervous system process and release held patterns.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">4. Graded Exposure / Graded Motor Imagery</h3>
      <p>Slowly and safely re-introducing movement and sensation to desensitize the nervous system. The key is pacing — staying within your "window of tolerance" while gradually expanding it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">5. Mindfulness-Based Approaches</h3>
      <p>Mindfulness helps you observe pain without the fear-reaction that reinforces it. ACT (Acceptance and Commitment Therapy) and MBSR (Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction) have good evidence for chronic pain.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1rem 0; border-left: 4px solid var(--teal);">
      <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">6. Somatic Tracking</h3>
      <p>A technique developed by Dr. John Sarno and refined by Alan Gordon and others — you notice the pain sensation without fear, cognitively reappraise it as safe, and shift your attention. Over time, this weakens the pain pathway.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Emerging approaches (2026 research)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Immune-targeted therapies</strong> — recent research highlights the role of non-neuronal cells (glial cells, immune cells) in maintaining central sensitization</li>
      <li><strong>Ethnopharmacological agents</strong> — compounds like myricitrin, Boswellia, and Ashwagandha are being studied for nociplastic pain</li>
      <li><strong>Brain circuit interventions</strong> — Stanford researchers (2026) identified distinct neural circuits for chronic vs acute pain, opening new targeted treatment possibilities</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What doesn't work as well</h2>
    <p>
      Treatments targeting <em>only</em> the body — surgery, injections, opioids — often fail for 
      neuroplastic pain because they don't address the brain-based mechanism. In fact, they can 
      sometimes reinforce the pain cycle by confirming to the brain that "something is wrong."
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="background: var(--teal-light); margin-top: 1.5rem;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <strong>Note:</strong> Always work with a healthcare professional. The best approach usually 
        combines multiple modalities and addresses sleep, stress, and emotional health alongside 
        brain-based therapy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div style="margin-top: 2rem; display: flex; gap: 1rem; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <a href="/resources" class="btn btn-primary">Resources →</a>
      <a href="/blog" class="btn btn-outline">Latest research posts</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
